# ZeyOS REST API [draft]

The ZeyOS Library REST API (or ZeyOS REST API) provides access to almost all of your ZeyOS data and gives you a powerful tool to connect third-party applications and other systems with ZeyOS, without having to write a custom ZeyOS app.

The REST API currently consists of two function groups:
- Authentication and session management
- Data access and data manipulation

Using a query language based on SQL, you can extract data from and manipulate data in your ZeyOS database, including simple table JOINs.

For more sophisticated tasks you can also use the [ZeyOS Core API and ZeyOS Library](http://www.zymba.info/] to build custom apps and web services for [ZeyOS](https://developer.zeyos.com/) and even deploy them to ZeyOS users via [ZeyConnect](https://www.zeyconnect.com/).

## Notational Conventions

Literal (verbatim) text is formatted like this: `Hello world`.
Please note that it may contain references or placeholders though which will then be documented.

A common placeholder is `{platform}` which should be replaced with the name of your platform.
For example, the base URL for API requests is `https://api.zeyos.com/{platform}/1.0/`, so if your platform were named `sandbox`, your API URL would be `https://api.zeyos.com/sandbox/1.0/`.

## Versioning Policy

The API is versioned with a **major** and a **minor version number**, making up the API **version number**.

The major version number may be increased along with the ZeyOS major version if there are semantic changes, while the minor version number may be increased when ZeyOS internals affecting the REST API change while keeping the same ZeyOS version number.

**Within the _same major and minor version number_, we reserve the right to _add_ HTTP headers, new parameters or new API endpoints (a.k.a. routes) _without_ breaking backwards compatibility and to _fix privilege escalation and any data leak issues_ (which _may_ break compatibility if you rely on access to otherwise inaccessible data), which is in _contrast_ to semantic versioning.**

We will however **not** change **documented semantics** of endpoints, HTTP headers, request parameters specified in the URI query string or the request body for routes from the point on they are **first made public and documented**.

While the REST API may stay the same, the underlying ZeyOS database itself _may_ change its schema on rare occasions (e.g. table or column changes, changes of type identifiers), thereby potentially breaking the REST API indirectly.

If this happens, the broken REST API version will be _phased out_, unless restoring compatibility through internal API code changes is deemed feasible, at our discretion.

All REST API versions **will stay** for as long as there are **no adverse availability-, security- or data-loss-related issues** and **no semantic or database schema changes**.

**Exceptions can be made to maintain or restore availability of ZeyOS, to mitigate attacks or to fix other critical security and data loss situations.**

Any other _incompatible_ changes to the REST API or to ZeyOS will be accompanied by a _new_ REST API version.

We will update our corresponding GitHub repositories to document pending changes several _weeks in advance_ whenever possible to give you time to update your systems and apps to prevent breakage and downtime.

We will also provide migration guides to help you transition to newer REST API versions.

## HTTP Methods

The REST API uses HTTP verbs according to the intended operation, also known as HTTP methods.

| Method | Description            |
| ------ | ---------------------- |
| DELETE | Delete data            |
| GET    | Read data              |
| HEAD   | Check for existence    |
| POST   | Create or update data  |
| PUT    | Create or replace data |

Depending on the requested resource, not all methods may be available.

Sometimes it may not be possible to use the proper HTTP method, for example because you are sending a request from an HTML form or use a restricted HTTP client.

For such cases, the REST API will check any `POST` request for an `X-HTTP-Method-Override` header or a `__method` form variable that specifies the actual intended method, in that order, and use the first non-empty value to route the request.

REST clients, browsers, proxies, web servers and security systems (firewalls, IDS/IPS...) may impose length restrictions on the URL, and thus on URL query parameters.
If your full REST API call URL exceeds 255 characters when using URL query parameters, we therefore recommend to specify the query parameters in a `POST` form variable `__query` and perform an HTTP `POST` with `X-HTTP-Method-Override: GET` (or whatever method you want to use).

## Return Values and Error Handling

The REST API currently only returns JSON data and an HTTP status code indicating the outcome of a request.

HTTP status code 200 is used to indicate a successful response, and the result will be an object with a `result` property as its only member.

```json
{"result":true}
```

When an error occurs, the HTTP status code will be outside the range of 200 - 399, and the JSON response will be an object with an `error` property with an error message.

```json
{"error":"System is in maintenance mode. Please try again later."}
```

We recommend that you treat any response which does not represent a valid JSON object, does not contain the `result` property or has an `error` property, or any HTTP status code outside the 200 - 399 range as an error.

HTTP status codes commonly used by the REST API to indicate failures:

|  Code | Reason                               |
| ----- | ------------------------------------ |
|  200  | No errors.                           |
|  201  | An object was created.               |
|  400  | Generic error / bad request.         |
|  401  | Unauthorized.                        |
|  403  | Access forbidden / permission denied.|
|  404  | Requested resource cannot be found.  |
|  409  | Conflict with an existing resource.  |
|  410  | Resource is gone.                    |
|  500  | Generic error, no details available. |
|  501  | Function not implemented.            |

## Authentication and Session Management

The REST API provides two means of authentication, a token-based mechanism and [HTTP Basic Access Authentication](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basic_access_authentication) via user name and password.
Token authentication is recommended for any applications that separate sign-in from interaction with ZeyOS and is likely safer than using user name and password because only a revocable token needs to be persisted.
HTTP Basic Access Authentication on the other hand provides compatibility with existing HTTP clients and can be less complex than managing token sessions when only single, "one-shot" requests should be performed.

If _both_ a token and Basic Access Authentication credentials are provided, token authentication will be used, ignoring any given user name and password, even if token authentication fails.

### Token Authentication

Token authentication relies on ZeyOS's token authentication mechanism, which is also exposed to [Zymba](http://www.zymba.info/docs/ZeyOS.TokenAuth/#validate) and [iXML](http://www.ixmldev.com/docs#auth:validate).

Tokens are linked to *identifiers* which should be specific to both the accessing app and device.
This allows devices to renew their tokens independently.

To obtain a new token (and invalidate any previous token for an identifier), call the REST API URI `/{platform}/1.0/auth` using `PUT` or `POST` and specify the user name, password and the app / device identifier as described below.

Token authentication works by including the `Zeyos-Api-Token` header in your request with the identifier, followed by a colon `:` and the obtained token string, as the value, e.g. `Zeyos-Api-Token: com.example.myapp.dev1138:2a3e4ec88e66138253a69da3406841fccb1c998e`.

### HTTP Basic Access Authentication

The REST API server itself will _not_ advertise HTTP Basic Access Authentication capabilities by default, i.e. it will not send a `WWW-Authenticate` response header, unless the request includes a URL query parameter `__auth=basic` or was attempted using this authentication method and failed.
However, the REST API will accept and verify an `Authorization: Basic ...` request header if one is supplied (and no authentication token was provided).

## Data Access and Data Manipulation

Database table rows can be loaded by performing a `GET` with the table name and the database record ID as the path, e.g. `GET /{platform}/1.0/notes/1`.

This will return a JSON-encoded object with the record's columns as properties of the `result` sub-object:

```json
{
    "result": {
        "ID": "1",
        "owneruser": null,
        "ownergroup": null,
        "creator": null,
        "assigneduser": null,
        "creationdate": "1406564511",
        "lastmodified": "1406564511",
        "visibility": "0",
        "name": "To Do",
        "status": "0",
        "text": "Document API",
        "contenttype": "text\/plain",
        "size": "0",
        "binfile": "189330609"
    }
}
```

To load all notes (up to the REST API's internal limit, or to a limit specified with `n=...`, whichever is less), simply omit the ID: `GET /{platform}/1.0/notes`.

If you also want to load extensional data (_"extdata"_), add a `GET` parameter `extdata=1`.
This will include a sub-object `extdata` for each returned object.

To create a record, send a `PUT` request with with the record's data.

Records are updated by sending a `POST` request with data to update.
Data can either be specified as URL-encoded form variables in the `POST` body or as JSON.

`PUT` and `POST` may specify data either in URL-encoded form (`Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded`, e.g. `name=ACME&city=New+York`) or as JSON (`Content-Type: application/json`).
The latter encoding should be preferred for `PUT` for consistency with the HTTP standard.

Unspecified values will not be modified.
In the case of `PUT`, this means that such values will be initialized with their default values as specified in the database table definition (if `creationdate` and `lastmodified` columns are unspecified, the REST API will fill them with the current date and time).

When using URL-encoding, values are specified as strings and will be converted automatically by the database to the columns' data types, therefore `name=` _(empty)_ would assign the empty string to `name`.

In order to specify NULL values, the REST API introduces a special notation with a prefixed minus sign `-`, e.g. `-name=`.
Note that in this case, any value supplied after the equal `=` character will be ignored.

To add or update extensional data, `extdata` fields may be specified in an `extdata` sub-object, i.e. as a URL-encoded HTTP form variable `extdata[<name>]=<string-value>` (in the request body), or as JSON as shown below:

```json
{
    "name": "My Record",
    "extdata": {
        "iban" : "BE62 5100 0754 7061",
        "count": 25,
        "valid": true
    }
}
```

Any previously existing extdata values will be overwritten with the new values.

Unspecified extdata values however remain untouched unless you also specify a form variable or top-level JSON object property `-extdata=` to remove all existing values.

Specifying `-extdata=` without later supplying any `extdata` fields will remove all extensional data.

When an entity record is created or updated, a "monitor" record (a log entry in the `records` table with `flag` set to `3`; see [ZeyOS schema documentation](http://schema.zeyos.com/)) will be created, unless you specify the URI query parameter `monitor=0`.

`PUT` requests on tags will yield `true` if the tag was linked to the specified entity.

`PUT` requests on database tables / entities will return the database record ID, i.e. the created row's primary key while `POST` requests will return `true` on success.

If you instead want to get the updated record after such a `PUT` or `POST`, specify a URI query parameter `object=1`, e.g. `POST /{platform}/1.0/accounts/42?object=1`.
This can be combined with the `extdata` flag to retrieve associated extensional data at the same time.

## Database Tables with Visibility Flag

Please note that this API provides low-level access to database records in the sense that `DELETE` operations will actually invoke an SQL `DELETE` regardless of any `visibility` table column.

If you want to soft-delete or archive a record on a table with a `visibility` column, set the column to the proper value mark the record as (soft-)deleted or archived.

| Visibility Flag | Description    |
| --------------- | -------------- |
|        0        | Regular object |
|        1        | Archived       |
|        2        | Soft-deleted   |

Please refer to the [ZeyOS Schema documentation](http://schema.zeyos.com/) for tables with a `visibility` flag (in the [_Columns_ section](http://schema.zeyos.com/columns.byColumn.html#columns).

## SQL via REST

The REST API exposes the ZeyOS Library's SQL query builder API, giving developers simple access to ZeyOS data.

Let's start with an example, searching for a text note where the name is `Vacation` or which contains the text `Jul`, followed by `2014` (e.g. `Jul 2014` or `July 28, 2014`):

```
GET /{platform}/1.0/notes
?a=n
&s=["n.text"]
&w[]=or
&w[]=["name", "Vacation"]
&w[]=["text","Jul%2014","ILIKE"]
&w[]=["text"]
&w[]=ea
&o[]=lastmodified
&o[]=creationdate-
&n=100
&i=200
```

Other than querying for rows, it is also possible to determine the row count with `q=c` or to obtain the SQL statement via `q=s`.

| Parameter |  Type       | Description                              | Example                  |
| --------- | ----------- | ---------------------------------------- | ------------------------ |
| `a`       | string      | Alias                                    | `a=note`                 |
| `d`       | bool        | DISTINCT                                 | `d=1`                    |
| `s`       | string/json | SELECT (see below)                       | `s[]=ID`                 |
| `m`       | string/json | Case-insensitive text search (see below) | `m=Anna`                 |
| `w`       | string/json | WHERE (see below)                        | `w[]=["name","Holiday"]` |
| `j`       | string/json | JOIN (see below)                         | `j[]=["contact"]`        |
| `g`       | string      | GROUP BY; name of column to group by     | `g[]=name`               |
| `o`       | string      | ORDER BY; column name plus optional "+"  for ascending, "-" for descending order and "F" / "L" for `NULLS FIRST` / `NULLS LAST` | `o[]=creationdate-` |
| `n`       | int         | LIMIT                                    | `n=25`                   |
| `i`       | int         | OFFSET                                   | `i=100`                  |
| `q`       | string      | Query: `c` for `COUNT`, `s` for the SQL  | `q=s`                    |
| `x`       | bool        | Set to `1` (or `true` when using JSON) to obtain numerically indexed columns (default: associative keys). | `x=1`                    |


### SELECT parameters

`SELECT` columns are given as `s[<index>]=<column>` or `s[<index>]=[<column>, <alias>]`, where `index` may be omitted (it will be inferred automatically from the order the columns are specified).

Examples:

```
s[]=ID
s[0]=text
s[]=["postalcode","pc"]
```

### Case-Insensitive Text Search

The REST API exposes a search function which behaves like the search text boxes in ZeyOS, performing a search for all supplied terms.

For example, the query `m=Hello+world` (`+` denotes a URL-encoded space) on the `appointments` table basically creates this `WHERE` condition:
```
(
    (
        LOWER("name") LIKE '%hello%' OR
        LOWER("location") LIKE '%hello%'
    ) AND (
        LOWER("name") LIKE '%world%' OR
        LOWER("location") LIKE '%world%'
    )
)
```

The search runs on pre-defined columns specific to each table that are likely to be shared among few rows only, e.g. a name, an identifier or a transaction number column.

You can find a list of considered columns in the parameter documentation for the list API call of each table.

Terms are broken up when space (whitespace) characters are encountered; to specify terms with spaces, double quotes `"` may be used, e.g. `m="Hello+world"`.

### WHERE

`WHERE` conditions must be specified as JSON: `w[<index>]=[<column>, <value>, <operator>]`, where `<index>`, `<value>` and `<operator>` are optional and may be omitted.

There are special "conditions" to create sub-conditions, namely `and` and `or`:

```
w[]=and
w[]=or
```

Both start a sub-condition which must be closed with `el` (end level) or `ea` (end all).
`el` closes the currently open sub-condition while `ea` closes all sub-conditions.

You can think of `and` / `or` to be equivalent to opening parentheses `(` and the respective conjunction / disjunction within the sub-condition and `el` to correspond to a closing parenthesis `)`.

Consequently, `ea` is a shortcut for as many `el` clauses as necessary to terminate all open sub-conditions.

Currently, the following operators are supported for `WHERE` (aliases may be used in place of the specified operator):

| Operator      | SQL Equivalent                     | Example                          | Aliases           |
| ------------- | ---------------------------------- | -------------------------------- | ----------------- |
| `n`           | `<column> IS NULL`                 | `["record",null,"n"]`            | `NULL`            |
| `nn`          | `<column> IS NOT NULL`             | `["record",null,"nn"]`           | `NOT_NULL`        |
| `=`           | `<column> = <value>`               | `["company","Zeyon","="]`        | `EQUAL` (default, can be omitted) |
| `!=`          | `<column> <> <value>`              | `["ID",5,"!="]`                  | `NOT_EQUAL`       |
| `ge`          | `<column> >= <value>`              | `["amount",100.00,"ge"]`         | `GREATER_EQUAL`   |
| `gt`          | `<column> > <value>`               | `["amount",100.00,"gt"]`         | `GREATER_THAN`    |
| `le`          | `<column> <= <value>`              | `["amount",100.00,"le"]`         | `LESS_EQUAL`      |
| `lt`          | `<column> < <value>`               | `["amount",100.00,"lt"]`         | `LESS_THAN`       |
| `in`          | `<column> IN <value>`              | `["status",[0,1],"in"]`          | `IN`              |
| `!in`         | `<column> NOT IN <value>`          | `["status",[5,6],"!in"]`         | `NOT_IN`          |
| `b`           | `<column> BETWEEN <a> AND <b>`     | `["status",[0,4],"b"]`           | `BETWEEN`         |
| `!b`          | `<column> NOT BETWEEN <a> AND <b>` | `["status",[5,9],"!b"]`          | `NOT_BETWEEN`     |
| `LIKE`        | `<column> LIKE <value>`            | `["text","%Jack%","LIKE"]`       |                   |
| `ILIKE`       | `<column> ILIKE <value>`           | `["text","%christmas%","ILIKE"]` |                   |
| `!`           | `NOT <column>`                     | `["status",null,"!"]`            | `NOT`             |
| `!v`          | `NOT <value>`                      | `["status",0,"!v"]`              | `NOT_VALUE`       |

The operators `=` and `!=` will also handle `null` and array values properly.
The following conditions on the left- and right-hand sides are equivalent:

```
["record",null,"n"]      ["record",null]
["record",null,"nn"]     ["record",null,"!="]
["status",[0,1],"in"]    ["status",[0,1]]
["status",[5,6],"!in"]   ["status",[5,6],"!="]
```

For example, the SQL condition `WHERE (a = 1 OR b = 'x')` would be written as

```
w[]=or                     #  (, use "OR"
w[]=["a",1]                #      a = 1
w[]=["b","x"]              #      b = 'x'
w[]=el                     #  )
```

A more complex example:

```sql
WHERE
    (creationdate >= 1234567890) AND
    (
        (company ILIKE 'Zeyon Tech%' AND country = 'CA') OR
        (company = 'Zeyon GmbH & Co. KG' AND country = 'DE')
    )
```

becomes

```
w[]=and                                           # (, use "AND"
  w[]=["creationdate",1234567890,"ge"]            #   (creationdate >= 1234567890)
  w[]=or                                          #   (, use "OR"
    w[]=and                                       #     (, use "AND"
      w[]=["company","Zeyon Tech%","ILIKE"]       #       company ILIKE 'Zeyon Tech%'
      w[]=["country","CA"]                        #       country = 'CA'
      w[]=el                                      #     )
    w[]=and                                       #     (, use "AND"
      w[]=["company","Zeyon GmbH & Co. KG"]       #       company = 'Zeyon GmbH & Co. KG'
      w[]=["country","DE"]                        #       country = 'DE'
w[]=ea                                            # )))
```

In a real query, we would then need to URL-encode the query parameters to get this:

```
w%5B%5D=and&
w%5B%5D=%5B%22creationdate%22%2C1234567890%2C%22ge%22%5D&
w%5B%5D=or&
w%5B%5D=and&
w%5B%5D=%5B%22company%22%2C%22Zeyon%20Tech%25%22%2C%22ILIKE%22%5D&
w%5B%5D=%5B%22country%22%2C%22CA%22%5D&
w%5B%5D=el&
w%5B%5D=and&
w%5B%5D=%5B%22company%22%2C%22Zeyon%20GmbH%20%26%20Co.%20KG%22%5D&
w%5B%5D=%5B%22country%22%2C%22DE%22%5D&
w%5B%5D=ea
```

### JOIN

For security reasons and simplicity, the REST API limits SQL JOINs to a subset of *"managed" JOINs* on tables related to the main table you are querying.

Managed JOINs are defined by specifying the foreign key column, optionally together with the table name, the JOIN type (`INNER` for `INNER JOIN`, `LEFT` for `OUTER LEFT JOIN`) and an alias for the joined table.

        j[]=[<column>, <table>, <join type>, <alias>]

All parameters but `<column>` are optional.

The alias parameter can be a string specifying the alias for the _joined_ table or an object that maps _table names to aliases_.
It **must** be specified only when any of the involved tables are aliased.

For example, if we were to query the `accounts` table and wanted to JOIN it with its assigned `contacts` record via `accounts.contact`, we would use

```
GET /{platform}/1.0/accounts
?j[]=["contact"]
```

Using the `JOIN`, we could use any column from the `contacts` table to limit our search:

```
GET /{platform}/1.0/accounts
    ?j[]=["contact"]
    &w[]=["contacts.company","Zeyon Technologies, Inc."]
```

It is also possible to JOIN on already joined tables ("transitive" JOINs).

In the simplest case, you provide the first JOIN from the main table and then the second from the first joined table to the third.

Let us consider this query:

```sql
SELECT *
FROM records
JOIN users ON records.creator = users.ID
JOIN contacts ON users.contact = contacts.ID
LIMIT 5
```

The REST API query would then look like this:

```
GET /{platform}/1.0/records
    ?j[]=["creator", "records"]
    &j[]=["contact", "users"]
    &n=5
```

Transitive JOINs are determined automatically, based on already defined JOINs.

Things get more complicated when aliases are used as these may introduce ambiguities.
The REST API then needs to know which table uses which alias, so you have to specify them explicitly.

When aliases are used in joining tables, they must be specified in the JOIN definition.
For example, the query

```sql
SELECT *
FROM records
JOIN users AS u ON records.creator = u.ID
LIMIT 5
```

would be written as

```
GET /{platform}/1.0/records
    ?a=r
    &j[]=["creator", "records", "INNER", "u"],
    &n=5
```

If the table for which the JOIN column is given is aliased (the `records` table in the example above), **both** tables and their aliases must be declared, e.g.

```sql
SELECT *
FROM records AS r
JOIN users AS u ON r.creator = u.ID
JOIN contacts AS c ON u.contact = c.ID
LIMIT 5
```

would then be:

```
GET /{platform}/1.0/records
    ?a=r
    &j[]=["creator", "records", "INNER", { "records": "r", "users": "u" }],
    &j[]=["contact", "users", "INNER", { "users": "u", "contacts": "c" }]
    &n=5
```

or in JSON

```json
{
    "a": "r",
    "j": [
        [
            "creator",
            "records",
            "INNER",
            {
                "records" : "r",
                "users"   : "u"
            }
        ],
        [
            "contact",
            "users",
            "INNER",
            {
                "users"   : "u",
                "contacts": "c"
            }
        ]
    ],
    "n": 5
}
```

# Group Authentication and Session Management

## Authentication [/auth{?object}{?settings}]

The authentication API yields the authenticated user's details when requesting`GET /{platform}/1.0/auth` or `POST /{platform}/1.0/auth?object=1`.
The returned data object contains most of the `users` table columns, permissions and possibly an (incomplete) `contact` sub-object that looks like this:

```json
"contact": {
    "ID": "1493",
    "lastname": "Ple",
    "firstname": "Exam",
    "email": "user@example.com",
    "gravatar": "b58996c504c5638798eb6b511e6f49af",
    "picbinfile": null
}
```

If the authenticated user does not have a contact assigned, the `contact` property will be `null` instead.

