# Group Batch Requests

## Specifying Commands

Performing multiple requests one at a time requires multiple network round-trips and consumes more resources, making them slow and expensive.

Therefore, ZeyOS exposes a REST API route for batch requests to which you can bundle and send multiple requests for processing and retrieve the results upon completion.

A batch request is specified as an _array of commands_ (a **command block**) and should be sent in JSON form using the `Content-Type: application/json` request header.
Alternatively, you could also send batch requests as URL-encoded `POST` data, although this is not recommended.

By default, the result of a batch request is the outcome of the _last command_ in the batch, but you can also obtain other or all results by using special commands.

Commands can be **assignments**, **settings**, **requests** or **entire command blocks**, i.e. command blocks are _nestable_.

Settings that accept a boolean `true` or `false` will default to `true` when the _value is unspecified_.
They are _not_ inherited by nested command blocks and will default to `false` when the _setting is not specified_ at all.

**All commands return a result.**
Settings will return the _setting's value_ after the assignment.

When a batch request is run, a result block will be assembled to store the results of each executed command, using the _same index_ that is used for the corresponding command.

The result of a _command block_ is the result of the block's _last command_.

Currently, the following commands are recognized:

### Assignments

- `=<ref-string>`
  Returns a string assembled according to `<ref-string>`.

  This may contain _path references_ to results previously obtained in the form `{{<ref-path>}}`.

  If the string consists of `{{<ref-path>}}` only, that result will be returned as-is, i.e. without any string conversion, but you can use the `string` modifier if necessary (e.g. `{{string:result}}`).

  Any additional characters before or after such a result reference, or multiple references will automatically convert all referenced results to strings.

  For a literal `{`, prepend it with a backslash, i.e. `\{`.
  However, you only need to backslash-escape if you have two consecutive opening curly braces `{{`, and only the first brace, i.e. `\{{` is sufficient.

- `all`
  Returns all results from the previously executed commands and stores that as a result.

- `select=<ref-path>`
  Returns the resolved result referenced by the given path.

**See also the section _Referencing Results_ for more details on paths and result references.**

### Settings

- `dry_run[=true|false]`
  If `true`, ZeyOS requests will not be executed, and the parsed command will be returned instead.

- `resume_on_fail[=true|false]`
  If set to `true`, batch execution will proceed even if an error occurs, and the failed commands will yield an object with an `error` property as they do for regular requests.
  When using this setting, transactions must be disabled or be confined to a nested command block below the current block.

- `transaction[=true|false]`
  Enables or disables database transactions for all subsequent commands in the command block until this setting is changed again.

  Within an enabled transaction, _all_ changes by commands in it that access the database will become effective and visible _only if and after_ all database-accessing commands have succeeded.
  If _any one_ command fails, all subsequent commands in the transaction _will also fail_ when they access the database, and all transactional changes will be _rolled back_ after the last executed command in the transactional sequence.

### Requests

A request is given as an object with at least a `path` property.

An HTTP method may be specified in the `verb` property and will default to `GET` if omitted.
An object of URL query parameters can be supplied via `query`, and form variables as sent by a `POST` request can be supplied via `body`, also as an object.

For example, the request `GET /records?n=2&o[]=lastmodified-` would be equivalent to:

```json
{
    "verb" : "GET",              // Default, may be omitted
    "path" : "/records",
    "query": {
        "n": 2,
        "o": [
            "lastmodified-"
        ]
    },
    "select": "result"           // Optional. Selects the specified path as the result.
}
```

You may specify a `select` in the request object to reduce the return value to what you actually need.
Resolution works very much like the `select=<ref>` assignment mentioned earlier, however paths are relative to the request, i.e. `"select": "result"` would fetch the request's `result` property.

## Referencing Results

As mentioned in the previous section, several commands allow access to previous results by specifying their position in the batch request.

Positions, _paths_ or _path references_ are a bit similar to file system directory paths or XPath specifications.
In fact, we use a (forward) slash `/` to separate path components.

A component addresses an element relative to the current command block.

A command block is numerically indexed, from index 0 to _n_ - 1 if the block consists of _n_ commands.
Therefore within a block, `3` refers to the result of the command at index `3`, which is the _fourth_ element in the block.

Parent blocks are accessible as `..`, so `../0` refers to the very first result in the parent block.

The top-level (root) command block can be accessed by specifying a sufficient number of `../`, or by a `/` at the very beginning of the path, e.g. `/2`.

If a result is an object, an array or a string, a sub-element of it may be addressed by its respective key / index.
For example, the property `name` of an object (in JSON terminology) `../2/5` is accessible as `../2/5/result/name`.

Invalid references will produce **error objects** `{ "error": ... }` and will **stop batch execution**, unless `resume_on_fail` is enabled.

The selection may be processed further by prepending the selection path with so-called _modifiers_, separated by a colon `:`, e.g. `json:result`.
Modifiers may be stacked and are processed from right (inner-most) to left, i.e. `uri:json:result` would first JSON-encode the `result` property and then URL-encode the JSON string.

This API version supports these modifiers:

| Modifier   | Description                             | Sample result                     | Resulting output         |
| ---------- | --------------------------------------- | --------------------------------- | ------------------------ |
| `csv`      | Produces a comma-separated list         | Array  `[ 1, 2, 3 ]`              | `1,2,3`                  |
| `entities` | Escapes XML/HTML entities               | String `x > y`                    | `x &gt; y`               |
| `json`     | Converts the selection to a JSON string | Object `{ "ID": 2, "name": "X" }` | `{"ID":2,"name":"X"}`    |
| `string`   | Converts the selection to a string      | Boolean `true`                    | `1` (as a string)        |
| `uri`      | URL-encodes the string result           | String `x > y`                    | `x%20%3E%20y`            |

A special "flattening" wildcard `*` can be used to select all properties in an array or object
For example, `result/*/ID` would yield the ID property of all returned objects in the result set such as `[24,31,32]`, rather than this:

```json
{
    "result": [
        {
            "ID": "24",
            ...
        },
        {
            "ID": "31",
            ...
        },
        {
            "ID": "32",
            ...
        }
    ]
}
```

To specify a literal slash `/`, backslash `\`, asterisk `*` or a colon `:` as part of the key, prepend it with a backslash to escape it, e.g. `result/paths/C\:\\Windows`.

