# Group Files
This route is read-only, i.e. only `GET` and `HEAD` requests are allowed.
The `files` table is considered an extension to the `records` table and therefore can only be modified through a `PUT` or `POST` to [`records`](#/reference/records).

The REST API will serve a `Content-Disposition` header for the `files/<id>/download` sub-route detailing the file name and whether the file should be treated as an attachment or be handled inline (if supported).

For security reasons, only files with MIME types `application/pdf`, `audio/*`, `image/*` and `video/*` can and will be served inline by default, while all others will always have a `Content-Disposition: attachment` header which advises browsers to present a download prompt.

PDFs, audio, video and image files can be requested as an attachment by specifying the query parameter `disposition=attachment` in the URL.

Additionally, the response will include the headers `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff` and `Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; base-uri '.invalid'; referrer no-referrer;` which will instruct Chrome and Internet Explorer to not override the MIME type based on content and prevent current web browsers from executing scripts that may have been uploaded by users.


file has the following attributes:

* ID (int8)
* record (int8)
* filename (text)
* mimetype (text)
* size (int4)
* binfile (int4)


